      <header class="post-head">
        <span class="mono label meta">Setúbal · 16 July 2026 · 5 min read</span>
        <h1>Setúbal is quietly becoming a place people build companies.</h1>
        <p class="dek">Thirty-five minutes from Lisboa, with lower costs and a better life. Here's why talent and startups are looking south.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-hero"><img src={hero} alt="A private office with a view over Setúbal" /></div>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>For years the story of Portuguese tech was a Lisbon story. That's changing. As the capital gets more crowded and more expensive, founders and remote workers are doing the obvious maths — and a lot of them are landing in <strong>Setúbal</strong>, on the peninsula just south of the city.</p>

        <h2>Close to Lisboa, without living in it</h2>
        <p>Setúbal is roughly <strong>35 minutes from Lisboa</strong>. Close enough for the meeting, the airport, the client dinner. Far enough that you get sea, hills, a real city centre, and rents that haven't lost touch with reality. You keep access to the Lisbon ecosystem while getting your evenings and your budget back.</p>

        <h2>The maths just works</h2>
        <p>Lower cost of living. Lower cost of workspace. Shorter commutes — often none at all. For a freelancer that's more margin; for a startup it's more runway. The same monthly spend buys a noticeably better standard of living here than it does thirty minutes north.</p>

        <blockquote>Better light, lower costs, and a coastline. It's not a compromise — it's an upgrade.</blockquote>

        <h2>Quality of life is a hiring advantage</h2>
        <p>Talent follows lifestyle now. Beaches, the Arrábida hills, fresh food, a walkable centre — these aren't a distraction from work, they're what makes people stay. A team that lives well ships better and churns less. Increasingly, "where's the office?" is answered with somewhere people actually want to be.</p>

        <h2>Where 22cowork fits</h2>
        <p>A growing hub needs a serious place to work, and that's the gap we fill. A <a href="/blog/deep-focus-by-design">focused, well-built space</a> with a 10GB fibre connection, private underground parking, a soundproofed studio and a gym downstairs — the kind of infrastructure that used to mean moving to a capital city. Now it's here, on the peninsula, minutes from home.</p>

        <p>Setúbal doesn't need to become the next Lisbon. That's rather the point. It's becoming a very good place to do focused work and build something — and the people who've noticed are already here.</p>
